Description

In overall summary of research, continuous variables are expressed with mean, standard deviation as well as median with a range of values. To determine significant differences in continuous variables between 2 groups we use Mann Whitney test. Every group in categorical variables are summarized with frequency and percentage of the considered population, statistical comparison between these groups are performed using chi-square test. The survival curves are estimated with Kaplan-Meier method and the log-rank test is used to compare the differences between groups.

Cox proportional hazards model is applied in univariate and multivariate analysis of the influence on patients death risk. Selection of predictive variables is performed on the base of univariate models (p-value<0.05). According to these results, these factors are determined as important in univariant analysis: sex, age, stage of lung cancer, pathological T stage, pathological N stage and surgical approach, resection type and comordibites: kidney failure, COPD, insulin dependent diabetics, illability of circulatory system.

In multivariate Cox analysis we estimate hazard ratio on the entire cohort of patients and controlling pathological N stage.

All tests were two-sided, and a P-value < 0.05 was considered statistically significant, to pairwise comparison of more than 2 groups the FDR adjustment is applied.. All analyses are performed using survival and survminer packages in R software.
